column1: Who will win the election for North Carolina's 13th Congressional District in 2022?
column5: ['The Democratic Party candidate', 'The Republican Party candidate', 'Someone else']

column6: AP called it. Didn't go the way the expert consensus thought it would.
A characteristic example where almost every model got it wrong:
60% of voting in with Dem having commanding lead. Virtually impossible for comeback.
The prediction markets, poll aggregates, and forecasts are nearly unanimous: this one is red.

Interesting race, to say the least. The odds are 3-1 for Hines (R) over Nickel (D) according to the aggregators. The professional forecasters are little more circumspect, with only Sabato edging out of toss-up territory to lean Republican. This is an R+2 district according to Cook, it's a midterm election, and the President is a Democrat, so it seems like this one should be pretty easy to call, even when you factor in the, um, "candidate quality" issues with Hines. Anecdotal reporting from the ground seems to indicate a pretty split electorate. I wouldn't bet 3-1 on Hines, but I'm not calling this a toss-up, either. 60-40, Hines.

https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2022-election-forecast/house/north-carolina/13/ gives Hines (R) a 75% chance of winning, however there is only one recent poll (by a SurveyUSA, a form with a good rating), and this one sees Nickel ahead (+1). Not really sure what to make out of this...
CNalysis have just changed their NC-13 rating from "Tilt R" to "Toss-up": https://twitter.com/ChazNuttycombe/status/1566865839978172421
+3 GOP district in a +5 GOP year = strong GOP lead
deep red district gerrymandered to keep it that way
Republican are way up on all polls and states

The Republican Party defeated the Democratic Party in North Carolina's 13th Congressional District was Republican by a healthy 35 point margin. This election should be no different, with incumbent Ted Budd wins another term.
